tributions that cover different periods of the history of ancient pharmacology, from Greek, Byzantine, and Syriac medicine to the Rabbinic-Talmudic medical discourses. This collection opens up new synchronic and diachronic perspectives in the study of the ancient traditions of recipe-books and medical collections. Besides the highly influential Galenic tradition, the contributions will focus on less studied Byzantine and Syriac sources as well as on the Talmudic tradition, which has never been systematically investigated in relation to medicine. This inquiry will highlight the overwhelming mass of information about drugs and remedies, which accumulated over the centuries and was disseminated in a variety of texts belonging to distinct cultural milieus. Through a close analysis of some relevant case studies, this volume will trace some paths of this transmission and transformation of pharmacological knowledge across cultural and linguistic boundaries, by pointing to the variety of disciplines and areas of expertise involved in the process.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aScience. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aGreek medical encyclopedias.  aIntercultural history of knowledge and science.  aLate Antique pharmacology/ pharmacotherapy.  aTalmudic Medicine.1 aAmit, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhayro, Siam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBio, Anna Maria Ieraci, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuzzi, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalà, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesch, Franziska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeller, Markham J., e